Security Operations Fundamentals > [T1]: Protecting Business with Efficient SOC

Why do we need a SOC?

There is no doubt that Security Operation Centers (SOC) are essential for every modern organization. We have already explored what a SOC is, but in this section, we will discuss the main reasons behind the need for an efficient Security Operation Center. 

 

Protect the Business and its Clients

The most obvious reason is to protect your business and your clients. Imagine yourself working as a cyber defender for a major healthcare institution, and a breach happens. A breach consequence will not be limited to your organization; it goes far beyond that and impacts all patients engaged with the organization at any time. In other words, non-employees. Such events should remind you why you are on the defensive line and doing what you're doing. (Reminder: You are a Hero!)

 

Financial Losses

Another reason, highly connected to the first one, is business losses and, in some cases, going off business. According to IBM Security Intelligence, in 2021, financial industries have suffered, on average, $5.72 million in losses directly connected to data breaches. 

Figure - zoom in

 

Readiness

If a breach happens, you must ensure that you are well-prepared. Having a SOC will allow you to spot security gaps, plan what needs to be done and prioritize it. For example, a data breach of the personal information affected over 145 million Americans in 2017. The targeted business was a credit reporting company called "Equifax." Chinese black-hat hackers gained access during the attack because the security team failed to upgrade software. You can read more about the data breach here - How Chinese military hackers allegedly pulled off the Equifax data breach, stealing data from 145 million Americans. 

 

Compliance Requirements 

Many modern organizations must comply with industry standards and adhere to specific laws and regulations. For example, The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) is a security-related standard that every financial organization dealing with credit cards must comply with. Most of these standards require SOC capabilities. There is no guarantee that COMPLIANT = SECURE! Some compliant organizations have miserable security hygiene; we have seen it too many times. Compliance is a supportive tool and will never guarantee security because passing a compliance check is more of a procedural process than a technical one. Having a SOC will make it easier for organizations to comply with relevant industry security standards.
